In article <broweCGF2Do.Mrr@netcom.com> browe@netcom.com (William Rowe) writes:
>PGP uses IDEA to encrypt the message body. A random key is generated for
>this and encrypted via RSA and incorporated as part of the message header.

Why is RSA never used for a message body?  If RSA is cracked, then the IDEA
key can be recovered, and the whole message falls.  Is it just a matter of
speed?  (i.e. RSA is slow)
